In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To force a theme, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Detect current system theme
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time theme changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");
    // Update UI, refresh colors, etc.
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Reset to follow system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Key points:**

- **`RequestedTheme`** — read-only, reflects the OS-level setting.
- **`RequestedThemeChanged`** — fires whenever the OS theme toggles (the `AppThemeChangedEventArgs` carries the new value).
- **`UserAppTheme`** — read/write; set it to `AppTheme.Dark` or `AppTheme.Light` to override the system, or `AppTheme.Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- XAML resources tagged with `AppThemeBinding` (or `OnPlatform`/`OnIdiom` with theme keys) react automatically to both system and `UserAppTheme` changes.

**Example with `AppThemeBinding` in XAML:**

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

This switches color automatically whenever the effective theme changes — no code-behind needed for simple style swaps.
